ol.li:
For scaling, say row 1 is scaled by k,
\det{\begin{bmatrix} ka \amp kb \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}} \amp = ka(d) - kb(c) \amp = k\brac{ad - bc} = k \cdot \det{A}
The determinant is also scaled by k.

For row exchange, consider exchanging row 1 and 2,
\det{\begin{bmatrix} c \amp d \\ a \amp b \end{bmatrix} \amp = cb - ad \amp = -\brac{ad - bc} = -\det{A}
This row operations changes the sign of the determinant.

For row replacement, say R_2 + k R_1 \rightarrow R_2,
\det{\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c + ka \amp d + kb \end{bmatrix}} \amp = a(d + kb) - b(c + ka) \amp = ad - bc + abk - abk \amp = ad - bc = \det{A}
This row operation doesn't change the value of the determinant.
